Analysis of Air Quality Index in Allegheny County

Cailin De Zeeuw

October 14, 2022

Allegheny County Air Quality Index

The Allegheny County Health Department regularly tracks air quality at sites throughout the county. Given the impact of air quality on public health and Western Pennsylvania’s industrial history, this data is useful for analyzing local air pollution levels and their potential health implications. Monitoring is also useful for determining compliance with federal air quality standards.

The data in this analysis was downloaded from the Western Pennsylvania Regional Data Center. (https://data.wprdc.org/dataset/allegheny-county-air-quality/resource/4ab1e23f-3262-4bd3-adbf-f72f0119108b?view_id=7d5cdd3a-a08e-4131-a528-41734c71f64c)

The dataset includes 7 variables and almost 55,000 rows. Each row represents one measurement of air quality at a particular site, on a particular day, of a particular pollutant. This information is given in the 7 columns:

  1. “date” gives the date of observation in the format “Year-month-day” (e.g. “2016-01-01”). The range of dates is from January 1, 2016 to October 5, 2022.
  2. “site” gives the location where the measurement was taken. There are 15 sites at various locations around Allegheny County. Different sites have varying equipment, and therefore can measure different pollutants. Not every site has the same number of observations.
  3. “parameter” gives the type of pollutant being measured in the observation. For example, ozone, carbon monoxide (CO), nitrogen dioxide (NO2), and multiple types of particulate matter (PM). Definitions of the parameters can be found at https://data.wprdc.org/dataset/allegheny-county-air-quality/resource/01297a0a-4160-41b3-8caf-90f7857ab7bd
  4. “index_value” is the quantitative measurement of the parameter. This value is what indicates the level of that pollutant present at the time and place of observation. Air Quality Index (AQI) is
  5. “description” provides a qualitative measure of the health impacts of pollutant level or AQI. For example, the observation could be at a “Good” level, an “Unhealthy” level, or somewhere in between.
  6. “health_advisory” provides a more detailed description of how local residents should interpret the AQI. For example, the advisory could read “People with asthma should consider limiting outdoor exertion.”
  7. “health_effects” provides a more detailed description of the health impacts of the current pollution level. For example, “Unusually sensitive individuals may experience respiratory symptoms.”

Exploratory Data Analysis

Grouping Like Data

Because this dataset includes information from different sites regarding different pollutants, any analysis must begin by subsetting the data into comparable groups. Useful analysis can only be done by directly comparing like parameters. For example, comparing a specific Ozone level to a level of Particulate Matter is not useful since they are harmful at different levels. Additionally, summarizing data across all sites in Allegheny County does not yield useful results. It is important to separate observations by site when making comparisons.

#filter data to group Particulate Matter parameters

aqi.pm <- aqi.AC %>%
  filter(grepl("PM", parameter)) #how to filter rows that contain a string from https://www.statology.org/filter-rows-that-contain-string-dplyr/

Above, I was able to filter the data for two specific pollutants: particulate matter and ozone. Because there are multiple varieties of particulate matter, there are more observations in the aqi.pm dataset than in the aqi.ozone dataset. There are 23390 observations of particulate matter, versus 7062 observations of ozone. When visualizing the spread of the index values by site, these plots also revealed that particulate matter is measured at more sites than ozone is, and there are more differences across sites.

Observing Variable Characteristics

description.colors <- c("green", "yellow", "red", "orange") #create color palette
boxplot(index_value ~ description, aqi.AC,
        xlab = "Qualitative AQI Description",
        ylab = "AQI",
        main = "Relationship between AQI and Description for Particulate Matter",
        col = description.colors,
        par(cex.axis= .75)) # code to resize labels for x-axis from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10488310/increase-size-of-boxplot-names-in-r

pm.description.summary <- aqi.pm %>%
  group_by(description) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(index_value), st.dev. = sd(index_value), 
            median = median(index_value),
            min = min(index_value), max = max(index_value))

knitr::kable(pm.description.summary, digits = 2)
description mean st.dev. median min max
Good 24.63 11.94 23 0 50
Moderate 61.29 9.66 58 51 100
Unhealthy 157.29 4.57 158 152 163
Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups 115.23 12.12 113 101 148

These side-by-side boxplots confirm the intuition that lower AQI values are labeled “Good” and high AQI values are labeled “Unhealthy.” They also illustrate the ranges of index values that these descriptors apply to for particulate matter pollutants. The table describes summary information of index values for each description. Note that the mean particulate matter AQI described as “Good” is 24.63, while the mean particulate matter AQI described as “Unhealthy” is much higher at 157.29. The range of AQI values described as “Unhealthy” appears to be smallest.

Looking for Trends

Analysis by Season

Measuring air quality data over time is important for understanding what factors might affect pollution levels. One question I have is whether the time of year impacts air quality.

#creating custom function to determine the season given the month
find_season <- function(date) {
  m <- month(date)
  case_when(m == 1 | m == 2 | m == 12 ~ "winter",   #referenced the "R Guide" from the Heinz class "Statistical Reasoning with 
            m == 3 | m == 4 | m == 5 ~ "spring",    #R" [90711] with Amelia Haviland for example of case_when()
            m == 6 | m == 7 | m == 8 ~ "summer",
            m == 9 | m == 10 | m == 11 ~ "fall")
}

#add column for season
aqi.AC <- aqi.AC %>%
  mutate(season = find_season(date))

#test season column: successful
aqi.AC$season[30000] #summer
## [1] "summer"
aqi.AC$date[30000] #august
## [1] "2019-08-22"
#add season column to other dataframes
aqi.pm <- aqi.pm %>%
  mutate(season = find_season(date))
aqi.ozone <- aqi.pm %>%
  mutate(season = find_season(date))

#visualizing PM AQI by season for a specific site
#filter data to Lawrenceville site
aqi.lawrenceville.pm <- aqi.AC %>%
  filter(site == "Lawrenceville" | 
         site == "Lawrenceville 2") %>%
  filter(grepl("PM", parameter))
#plot figure
season.colors <- c("orange","pink","green","blue")
boxplot(index_value ~ season, aqi.lawrenceville.pm,
        xlab = "Season",
        ylab = "AQI",
        main = "Particulate Matter AQI by Season in Lawrenceville",
        col = season.colors,
        par(cex.axis= .75))

At the Lawrenceville site, there appears to be some difference in AQI between seasons. Specifically, it appears that the mean AQI in summer is higher than that in the other three seasons. To investigate this possible trend, I will look at observations labeled as “Good” versus all other descriptions (including “Unhealthy,” “Moderate,” and “Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups.”)

#Creating figure to illustrate observations NOT described as "Good" by site and season
#add column to identify healthy AQI levels ("Good" as TRUE and all other descriptions as FALSE)
aqi.pm <- aqi.pm %>%
  mutate(healthy = description == "Good")

#creating ggplot object
season.site.plot <- aqi.pm %>%
  filter(healthy == FALSE) %>%
  filter(site != "Clairton",    #filtering out sites with missing seasons
         site != "Flag Plaza",
         site != "Glassport High Street") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = season, y = ..prop.., fill = site, group = 1)) 
                                      #code for bar graph with proportions from  
                                      #https://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/291083_2b0374fddc464ed08b4eb16c95d84075.html

#producing figure
season.site.plot + geom_bar(stat="count", position="dodge") + 
  facet_grid(~site) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  guides(fill = "none") + 
  ylab("Proportion of Observations Exceeding Healthy Levels") + 
  xlab("Season") +
  labs(title = "AQI Exceeds Healthy Levels Most in Summer")

Based on the figure above, there is a noticeable visual trend across sites: observations that exceed healthy AQI levels for particulate matter appear to increase in the summer season. To investigate this possible trend, I will perform further analysis on two specific sites: Pittsburgh and North Braddock.

#filter data for Pittsburgh site
aqi.pm.pitt <- aqi.pm %>%
  filter(site == "Pittsburgh")
#perform ANOVA analysis
anova.pitt <- aov(healthy ~ season, data = aqi.pm.pitt)
summary(anova.pitt)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
## season         3   1.66  0.5539     5.2 0.00143 **
## Residuals   1245 132.60  0.1065                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#filter data for North Braddock site
aqi.pm.brad <- aqi.pm %>%
  filter(site == "North Braddock")
#perform ANOVA analysis
anova.brad <- aov(healthy ~ season, data = aqi.pm.brad)
summary(anova.brad)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## season         3   0.13 0.04292   0.948  0.417
## Residuals   2626 118.93 0.04529

Pittsburgh site: Based on the ANOVA analysis, the season does impact the AQI levels. The p-value from the ANOVA is less than alpha=0.05, indicating that there are statistically significant differences between the “healthy” AQI levels by season.

North Braddock site: Based on the ANOVA analysis, the season does not impact the AQI levels. The p-value from the ANOVA is greater than alpha=0.05, indicating that there is no statistical difference between these groups.

Further investigation is needed to analyze the potential trend of higher proportions of unhealthy AQI levels occuring in the summer season.

Analyzing impacts of COVID-19 pandemic on AQI

Based on the observations from the above plots, I wondered if pollutant levels were affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. To perform this analysis, I will focus on the Lawrenceville site. However, further analysis at different sites would be required to draw strong conclusions.

#create dataframe for Lawrenceville "before covid"
aqi.lawrenceville.bc <- aqi.lawrenceville.pm %>%
  filter(date < "2020-03-14")
#create dataframe for Lawrenceville during the peak COVID year
aqi.lawrenceville.covid <- aqi.lawrenceville.pm %>%
  filter(date >= "2020-03-14" &
        date <= "2021-03-14")
#add column to lawrenceville dataframe indicating if the observation was taken during COVID
aqi.lawrenceville.pm <- aqi.lawrenceville.pm %>%
  mutate(COVID = date >= "2020-03-14" &
                date <= "2021-03-14")

#visualize AQI during COVID
boxplot(index_value ~ COVID, aqi.lawrenceville.pm,
        xlab = " ",
        ylab = "AQI",
        main = "Particulate Matter AQI during COVID-19 in Lawrenceville",
        col = "light blue",
        names = c("Not Peak Pandemic", "During COVID-19 Pandemic"),
        par(cex.axis= .75))

#calculate mean and standard deviation
aqi.covid <- aqi.lawrenceville.pm %>%
  group_by(COVID) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(index_value), st.dev.=sd(index_value))

Based on the visual differences between COVID times and non-COVID times in the boxplot and histogram, it appears that the pandemic did impact air quality. Specifically, it seemed that pollution levels decreased during the peak pandemic year. This could be explained by the shut-down that society experienced, which resulted in fewer cars on the road, and generally less commerce and industry.

To test the difference in means, I used a t test analysis. The results of the t test indicate that there is a statistically significant difference between AQI during peak pandemic, and AQI in other years, for particulate matter in Lawrenceville.

Finally, the scatterplot illustrates how AQI levels change across months for different years. While the 2020 data does not span all 12 months, it appears that beginning in April, the AQI levels decrease relative to most years. It should be noted that 2017 also experienced a dip at this time, but increased sooner than levels in 2020 did. Further investigation would be required to explain this dip during 2017. When the 2020 data cuts off during the summer, it appears that AQI levels were remaining low relative to trends of past years.
